# ABOUTME: Walking skeleton and iteration roadmap pipeline with PAR scope review and story splitting.
# ABOUTME: Reads extracted requirements/scenarios, defines ITER-0000, orders follow-on iterations, runs PAR scope review, writes roadmap.md.
workflow IterScope
  goal: "Define walking skeleton (ITER-0000) and ordered iteration roadmap from extracted requirements, with PAR scope review and story splitting for heterogeneous-dependency ACs"
  start: Start
  exit: Exit

  defaults
    model: claude-sonnet-4-6
    provider: anthropic
    max_retries: 3
    max_restarts: 20

  agent Start
    label: Start
    auto_status: true
    prompt:
      Acknowledge that the walking skeleton and roadmap pipeline is starting. Do not read or write any files. Do not run commands. Do not modify, create, or delete anything.

      End with exactly one of:
      STATUS: success
      STATUS: fail

      Always emit STATUS: success.

  agent Exit
    label: Exit
    auto_status: true
    prompt:
      Acknowledge that the walking skeleton and roadmap pipeline is complete. Do not read or write any files. Do not run commands. Do not modify, create, or delete anything.

      End with exactly one of:
      STATUS: success
      STATUS: fail

      Always emit STATUS: success.

  tool check_scope_resume
    label: "Check Scope Resume Point"
    timeout: 10s
    command:
      set -euo pipefail
      req_count=$(ls docs/iterations/requirements/*.md 2>/dev/null | wc -l | tr -d ' ') || req_count=0
      if [ "$req_count" -eq 0 ]; then
        printf 'no-requirements'
        exit 0
      fi
      if [ -f docs/iterations/roadmap.md ] && grep -q '## Walking skeleton' docs/iterations/roadmap.md; then
        printf 'has-roadmap'
        exit 0
      fi
      printf 'no-roadmap'

  agent no_requirements_exit
    label: "No Requirements Found"
    auto_status: true
    prompt:
      Requirements must be extracted before defining the walking skeleton and roadmap.

      The requirements directory docs/iterations/requirements/ is empty or does not exist.

      Please run iter_extract.dip first to extract requirements and behavior scenarios from your spec, then re-run this pipeline.

      STATUS: fail

  agent validate_existing_roadmap
    label: "Validate Existing Roadmap"
    auto_status: true
    prompt:
      Read and validate the existing roadmap at docs/iterations/roadmap.md.

      Check:
      1. The roadmap has a "## Walking skeleton" section with ITER-0000 defined
      2. Every STORY-NNNN cited in the roadmap exists in docs/iterations/requirements/
      3. Each iteration section has **Stories:**, **Rationale:**, **Status:**, and **Impacted scenarios:** fields
      4. At least one JOURNEY-NNNN scenario is cited as the walking skeleton's journey scenario

      Report what is valid and what is missing or broken.

      End with exactly one of:
      STATUS: success
      STATUS: fail

      Emit STATUS: success when the existing roadmap is complete and consistent (pipeline can exit). Emit STATUS: fail when the roadmap is missing fields, has broken citations, or is otherwise invalid (pipeline will rebuild).

  agent read_backlog
    label: "Read Backlog"
    model: gemini-3-flash-preview
    provider: gemini
    auto_status: true
    prompt:
      Read all epic files in docs/iterations/requirements/ — scan epic headers, story titles, status fields, and AC proof obligations. Also read docs/iterations/behavior-scenarios.md for scenario coverage.

      Write a backlog summary to .ai/iter-scope-temp/backlog_summary.md listing:
      - Total epics and total stories (pending vs done)
      - Total scenarios (surface vs journey), counting SCENARIO-NNNN and JOURNEY-NNNN separately
      - A matrix of which stories have scenario coverage vs which don't (cross-reference story titles/IDs against owning_stories fields in behavior-scenarios.md)

      Create the .ai/iter-scope-temp/ directory if it does not exist.

      HARD CONSTRAINT: Do NOT modify any files in docs/iterations/. Only write to .ai/iter-scope-temp/backlog_summary.md.

      End with exactly one of:
      STATUS: success
      STATUS: fail

      Emit STATUS: success when you wrote the backlog summary. Emit STATUS: fail only if you could not produce the summary due to a tool error.

  agent define_skeleton
    label: "Define Walking Skeleton"
    model: claude-opus-4-7
    reasoning_effort: high
    goal_gate: true
    auto_status: true
    prompt:
      You are defining the Walking Skeleton — ITER-0000 — for an iterative development project.

      Read:
      1. .ai/iter-scope-temp/backlog_summary.md
      2. All epic files in docs/iterations/requirements/
      3. docs/iterations/behavior-scenarios.md

      ## Walking Skeleton Requirements

      Select a SMALL cohesive set of stories from as many distinct epics as possible. The skeleton proves the end-to-end shape of the product works.

      MANDATORY:
      - ITER-0000 MUST include stories that close at least ONE journey scenario chain (JOURNEY-NNNN)
      - Prefer the core product journey over edge cases
      - The skeleton's FIRST task must be designing and building the E2E test harness
      - The skeleton must produce the first sentinel corpus entries

      Selection rule: "if someone ran just these stories, they should see a demo that proves the product exists AND have at least one passing journey scenario."

      ## Output

      Write your walking skeleton definition to .ai/iter-scope-temp/skeleton.md:

      ## Walking Skeleton (ITER-0000)
      **Intent:** <one-line description>
      **Design rationale:** <why these stories>
      **Journey scenario:** <JOURNEY-NNNN that must pass>
      **Stories committed:**
      - STORY-NNNN (EPIC-NNN) — <title>
      **Harness-first task:** Design and build E2E test harness before product features
      **Sentinel corpus seeds:** <which scenarios become sentinels>

      End with exactly one of:
      STATUS: success
      STATUS: fail

      Emit STATUS: success when skeleton.md is written and includes a journey scenario citation. Emit STATUS: fail only if you could not produce a valid skeleton definition.

  agent order_iterations
    label: "Order Iterations"
    model: claude-opus-4-7
    reasoning_effort: high
    goal_gate: true
    auto_status: true
    prompt:
      You are ordering the remaining stories (not in the walking skeleton) into follow-on iterations.

      Read:
      1. .ai/iter-scope-temp/skeleton.md (walking skeleton definition)
      2. All epic files in docs/iterations/requirements/
      3. docs/iterations/behavior-scenarios.md

      ## Rules

      - Each iteration = a sprint's worth of cohesive work. Granularity is judgment-based.
      - STORY SPLITTING: Check each story's ACs for dependency profiles. If some ACs can be satisfied in iteration N but others require subsystems from iteration N+M, SPLIT the story:
        1. Create version with satisfiable ACs for iteration N
        2. Create version with remaining ACs for iteration N+M
        3. Append a/b to the STORY-ID (e.g., STORY-0005a, STORY-0005b)
      - Each iteration lists impacted scenarios from behavior-scenarios.md
      - Look-ahead: does this iteration block or get blocked by neighbors?

      ## Output

      Write to .ai/iter-scope-temp/iterations.md — one section per iteration:

      ### ITER-NNNN — <name>
      **Stories:** STORY-NNNN, STORY-NNNN
      **Rationale:** <why together>
      **Impacted scenarios:** SCENARIO-NNNN, JOURNEY-NNNN
      **Look-ahead:** <blocks/blocked-by analysis>
      **Story splits:** <any stories split, with AC breakdown> or "None"

      End with exactly one of:
      STATUS: success
      STATUS: fail

      Emit STATUS: success when iterations.md is written. Emit STATUS: fail only if you could not produce a valid iteration ordering.

  tool init_scope_counter
    label: "Init Scope Round Counter"
    timeout: 5s
    command:
      set -euo pipefail
      mkdir -p .ai/iter-scope-temp
      printf '0' > .ai/iter-scope-temp/.scope_rounds
      printf 'initialized'

  tool check_citations
    label: "Check Story Citations"
    timeout: 15s
    command:
      set -euo pipefail
      rm -f .ai/iter-scope-temp/missing-ids.txt
      for f in .ai/iter-scope-temp/skeleton.md .ai/iter-scope-temp/iterations.md; do
        [ -f "$f" ] || continue
        { grep -oE 'STORY-[0-9]+[a-z]?' "$f" || true; } | sort -u | while IFS= read -r story_id; do
          base_id=$(printf '%s' "$story_id" | sed 's/[a-z]$//')
          if ! grep -qr "$base_id" docs/iterations/requirements/ 2>/dev/null; then
            printf '%s\n' "$story_id" >> .ai/iter-scope-temp/missing-ids.txt
          fi
        done
      done
      if [ -f .ai/iter-scope-temp/missing-ids.txt ]; then
        ids=$(sort -u .ai/iter-scope-temp/missing-ids.txt | tr '\n' ',' | sed 's/,$//')
        rm -f .ai/iter-scope-temp/missing-ids.txt
        printf 'citations-fail-%s' "$ids"
      else
        rm -f .ai/iter-scope-temp/missing-ids.txt
        printf 'citations-ok'
      fi

  agent fix_citations
    label: "Fix Citations"
    auto_status: true
    prompt:
      Read the citation check results — some STORY-NNNN IDs in .ai/iter-scope-temp/skeleton.md or .ai/iter-scope-temp/iterations.md do not match any story in docs/iterations/requirements/.

      Read:
      1. .ai/iter-scope-temp/skeleton.md
      2. .ai/iter-scope-temp/iterations.md
      3. All epic files in docs/iterations/requirements/ to find the correct IDs

      For each missing ID, find the story that was intended (by title match or context) and correct the ID in skeleton.md and/or iterations.md.

      If a cited story genuinely does not exist in the requirements, remove it and choose the closest existing story as replacement.

      Update both files with correct citations only.

      End with exactly one of:
      STATUS: success
      STATUS: fail

      Emit STATUS: success when you updated the temp files with corrected citations. Emit STATUS: fail only if you could not write the corrections.

  parallel par_scope_dispatch -> par_scope_reviewer_a, par_scope_reviewer_b

  agent par_scope_reviewer_a
    label: "PAR Scope Reviewer A — Structural Linkage"
    model: claude-opus-4-7
    provider: anthropic
    auto_status: true
    prompt:
      ## Competitive Context

      You are Reviewer A (Structural Linkage Specialist). A parallel reviewer with a DIFFERENT analytical lens is evaluating the same work. You will NOT see each other's findings. Score 5 points per serious/critical finding. False positives cost 3 points.

      ---

      ## Your Lens: Citation Integrity, Scenario Coverage, Story Decomposition

      You verify that the roadmap's structural links are correct and complete. You are a data integrity auditor.

      Read:
      1. .ai/iter-scope-temp/skeleton.md
      2. .ai/iter-scope-temp/iterations.md
      3. docs/iterations/requirements/ (all epic files)
      4. docs/iterations/behavior-scenarios.md

      ### 1. Citation Integrity (your PRIMARY focus)
      For EACH story ID in the skeleton and iterations:
      - Does STORY-NNNN exist in requirements/? (ID check)
      - Does the story card's description match how the roadmap uses it? (Semantic check)
      - Are all ACs present with proof obligations (behavioral_impact + proof_seam)?
      - Flag any story ID that appears in roadmap but NOT in requirements/

      ### 2. Scenario Coverage
      For EACH AC with behavioral_impact != "none":
      - Does a scenario exist in behavior-scenarios.md?
      - Is the proof seam correct (not weaker than declared)?
      - Does ITER-0000 close at least one JOURNEY scenario end-to-end?
      - Flag iterations that add observable behavior with zero scenario coverage

      ### 3. Story Splitting
      For each story: do all ACs have the same dependency profile? If AC-1 needs a database and AC-2 needs an API client, they should be in different iterations.
      - Flag stories with heterogeneous dependencies scoped whole into one iteration

      ## Report Format
      - **Citation Integrity:** PASS | [list of broken/missing citations]
      - **Scenario Coverage:** PASS | [list of uncovered ACs]
      - **Story Splitting:** PASS | [stories to split with AC breakdown]

      Conclude with specific structural fixes needed (if any), then end with exactly one of:
      STATUS: success
      STATUS: fail

      Emit STATUS: success when all three sections are PASS (this is your APPROVE verdict). Emit STATUS: fail when any section reports issues that need revision (this is your REVISE verdict). The aggregator routes failures into the adjustment loop.

  agent par_scope_reviewer_b
    label: "PAR Scope Reviewer B — Strategic Risk"
    model: claude-opus-4-7
    provider: anthropic
    auto_status: true
    prompt:
      ## Competitive Context

      You are Reviewer B (Strategic Risk Specialist). A parallel reviewer with a DIFFERENT analytical lens is evaluating the same work. You will NOT see each other's findings. Score 5 points per serious/critical finding. False positives cost 3 points.

      ---

      ## Your Lens: Scope Creep, Boxing-In, Iteration Ordering Risk

      You evaluate whether the roadmap sets up future iterations for success or failure. You think 3 iterations ahead.

      Read:
      1. .ai/iter-scope-temp/skeleton.md
      2. .ai/iter-scope-temp/iterations.md
      3. docs/iterations/requirements/ (all epic files)
      4. docs/iterations/behavior-scenarios.md

      ### 1. Scope Creep (your PRIMARY focus)
      - Is ITER-0000 minimal? Could ANY story be deferred without breaking the skeleton?
      - For each story in ITER-0000: is it structurally required for the skeleton, or is it nice-to-have?
      - Are follow-on iterations well-bounded (clear entry/exit criteria)?
      - Total story count per iteration: flag any iteration with >5 stories as potentially over-scoped

      ### 2. Boxing-In Look-Ahead
      For EACH iteration, simulate: "If I build this, what am I committing to?"
      - Hard coupling: does ITER-0000's architecture force ITER-0001 into a specific approach?
      - Premature abstraction: does any iteration build generics before proving the specific case?
      - Interface lock-in: does any iteration define a public API that later iterations would need to break?
      - Data model lock-in: does any iteration create schema that later iterations would need to migrate?

      ### 3. Iteration Ordering Risk
      - Could any later iteration be done EARLIER with less risk?
      - Are there dependency cycles between iterations?
      - Does the ordering maximize learning (riskiest unknowns first)?

      ## Report Format
      - **Scope Creep:** PASS | [stories to defer with rationale]
      - **Boxing-In:** PASS | [risks with specific downstream iterations affected]
      - **Ordering Risk:** PASS | [reordering recommendations]

      Conclude with specific strategic changes needed (if any), then end with exactly one of:
      STATUS: success
      STATUS: fail

      Emit STATUS: success when all three sections are PASS (this is your APPROVE verdict). Emit STATUS: fail when any section reports issues that need revision (this is your REVISE verdict). The aggregator routes failures into the adjustment loop.

  fan_in par_scope_join <- par_scope_reviewer_a, par_scope_reviewer_b

  agent par_scope_aggregate
    label: "PAR Scope Aggregate"
    model: gemini-3-flash-preview
    provider: gemini
    auto_status: true
    prompt:
      Read both PAR reviewer outputs from par_scope_reviewer_a and par_scope_reviewer_b.

      Each reviewer ended their report with STATUS: success (APPROVE) or STATUS: fail (REVISE).

      Aggregate the findings:
      - Same issue found by both reviewers = high confidence, must be addressed
      - Unique finding from one reviewer = still actionable, include it
      - Severity disagreement between reviewers = take the worst (higher) severity

      End with exactly one of:
      STATUS: success
      STATUS: fail

      Emit STATUS: success when both reviewers emitted STATUS: success (no revisions needed; pipeline proceeds to write_roadmap). Emit STATUS: fail when either reviewer emitted STATUS: fail; include a consolidated list of specific changes required so the adjustment agent can apply them.

  tool count_scope_rounds
    label: "Count Scope Review Rounds"
    timeout: 5s
    command:
      set -euo pipefail
      counter_file=".ai/iter-scope-temp/.scope_rounds"
      mkdir -p .ai/iter-scope-temp
      [ -f "$counter_file" ] || printf '0' > "$counter_file"
      n=$(cat "$counter_file")
      n=$((n + 1))
      printf '%s' "$n" > "$counter_file"
      if [ "$n" -ge 5 ]; then
        printf 'cap-reached'
      else
        printf 'continue'
      fi

  agent adjust_scope
    label: "Adjust Scope"
    max_turns: 200
    auto_status: true
    prompt:
      Read the scope review findings from par_scope_aggregate. Adjust skeleton.md and iterations.md to address all raised issues.

      Read:
      1. .ai/iter-scope-temp/skeleton.md
      2. .ai/iter-scope-temp/iterations.md
      3. docs/iterations/requirements/ (all epic files, if story splits are needed)

      Apply any recommended story splits by:
      1. Updating .ai/iter-scope-temp/skeleton.md and .ai/iter-scope-temp/iterations.md with the split story IDs (STORY-NNNNa, STORY-NNNNb)
      2. Updating the affected epic files in docs/iterations/requirements/ to reflect the split stories

      Address every issue called out by par_scope_aggregate (it emitted STATUS: fail because the reviewers found revisions). Update both temp files with the corrected scope.

      End with exactly one of:
      STATUS: success
      STATUS: fail

      Emit STATUS: success when you applied the adjustments and the temp files are updated (re-runs the citation check and PAR review). Emit STATUS: fail when you could not produce a coherent adjustment (pipeline force-accepts current scope and proceeds to write_roadmap).

  agent write_roadmap
    label: "Write Roadmap"
    model: claude-sonnet-4-6
    goal_gate: true
    auto_status: true
    prompt:
      Read .ai/iter-scope-temp/skeleton.md and .ai/iter-scope-temp/iterations.md.

      Write docs/iterations/roadmap.md in this exact format:

      # Roadmap

      ## Walking skeleton (ITER-0000)

      **Intent:** <one-line>
      **Design rationale:** <why>
      **Journey scenario:** JOURNEY-NNNN
      **Stories committed:**
      - STORY-NNNN (EPIC-NNN)
      **Status:** pending

      ## Iteration list

      ### ITER-0001 — <name>
      **Stories:** STORY-NNNN, STORY-NNNN
      **Rationale:** <why together>
      **Status:** pending
      **Impacted scenarios:** SCENARIO-NNNN, JOURNEY-NNNN
      **Look-ahead check:** <blocks/blocked-by>

      Continue for all iterations from iterations.md.

      If story splits were applied in iterations.md, also update the affected epic files in docs/iterations/requirements/ to reflect the split stories (STORY-NNNNa, STORY-NNNNb format).

      End with exactly one of:
      STATUS: success
      STATUS: fail

      Emit STATUS: success when docs/iterations/roadmap.md is written. Emit STATUS: fail only if you could not produce a valid roadmap.

  tool validate_roadmap
    label: "Validate Roadmap"
    timeout: 10s
    command:
      set -euo pipefail
      fail_reason=""
      if [ ! -f docs/iterations/roadmap.md ]; then
        printf 'roadmap-invalid-file-missing'
        exit 0
      fi
      if ! grep -q '## Walking skeleton' docs/iterations/roadmap.md; then
        printf 'roadmap-invalid-missing-walking-skeleton-section'
        exit 0
      fi
      iter_count=$(grep -c '^### ITER-' docs/iterations/roadmap.md 2>/dev/null || true)
      if [ "$iter_count" -eq 0 ]; then
        printf 'roadmap-invalid-no-iter-sections'
        exit 0
      fi
      if ! grep -q '\*\*Status:\*\*' docs/iterations/roadmap.md; then
        printf 'roadmap-invalid-missing-status-fields'
        exit 0
      fi
      if ! grep -q 'STORY-' docs/iterations/roadmap.md; then
        printf 'roadmap-invalid-no-story-refs'
        exit 0
      fi
      printf 'roadmap-valid'

  tool commit_roadmap
    label: "Commit Roadmap"
    timeout: 30s
    command:
      set -euo pipefail
      git add docs/iterations/
      if git diff --cached --quiet; then
        printf 'no-changes-skipped'
      else
        git commit -m "docs: add roadmap — walking skeleton with journey scenario + iteration plan"
        printf 'committed'
      fi

  edges
    Start -> check_scope_resume
    check_scope_resume -> no_requirements_exit    when ctx.tool_stdout = no-requirements     label: no_reqs
    check_scope_resume -> validate_existing_roadmap  when ctx.tool_stdout = has-roadmap      label: has_roadmap
    check_scope_resume -> read_backlog            when ctx.tool_stdout = no-roadmap          label: fresh
    check_scope_resume -> read_backlog
    no_requirements_exit -> Exit
    validate_existing_roadmap -> Exit             when ctx.outcome = success   label: valid
    validate_existing_roadmap -> read_backlog     when ctx.outcome = fail      label: invalid
    read_backlog -> define_skeleton
    read_backlog -> Exit                          when ctx.outcome = fail      label: backlog_failed
    define_skeleton -> order_iterations           when ctx.outcome = success   label: skeleton_defined
    define_skeleton -> Exit                       when ctx.outcome = fail      label: skeleton_failed
    order_iterations -> init_scope_counter        when ctx.outcome = success   label: ordered
    order_iterations -> Exit                      when ctx.outcome = fail      label: ordering_failed
    init_scope_counter -> check_citations
    check_citations -> par_scope_dispatch         when ctx.tool_stdout = citations-ok         label: citations_ok
    check_citations -> fix_citations              when ctx.tool_stdout startswith citations-fail  label: citations_bad
    fix_citations -> check_citations              restart: true
    fix_citations -> Exit                         when ctx.outcome = fail      label: fix_citations_failed
    par_scope_dispatch -> par_scope_reviewer_a
    par_scope_dispatch -> par_scope_reviewer_b
    par_scope_dispatch -> par_scope_aggregate     when ctx.outcome = fail      label: tolerated
    par_scope_reviewer_a -> par_scope_join
    par_scope_reviewer_a -> par_scope_join        when ctx.outcome = fail      label: reviewer_a_revise
    par_scope_reviewer_b -> par_scope_join
    par_scope_reviewer_b -> par_scope_join        when ctx.outcome = fail      label: reviewer_b_revise
    par_scope_join -> par_scope_aggregate
    par_scope_aggregate -> write_roadmap          when ctx.outcome = success   label: approved
    par_scope_aggregate -> count_scope_rounds     when ctx.outcome = fail      label: revise
    count_scope_rounds -> adjust_scope            when ctx.tool_stdout = continue       label: under_cap
    count_scope_rounds -> write_roadmap           when ctx.tool_stdout = cap-reached    label: force_accept
    adjust_scope -> check_citations               when ctx.outcome = success   restart: true   label: adjusted
    adjust_scope -> write_roadmap                 when ctx.outcome = fail      label: adjust_failed_force
    write_roadmap -> validate_roadmap             when ctx.outcome = success   label: written
    write_roadmap -> Exit                         when ctx.outcome = fail      label: write_failed
    validate_roadmap -> commit_roadmap            when ctx.tool_stdout = roadmap-valid        label: valid
    validate_roadmap -> write_roadmap             when ctx.tool_stdout startswith roadmap-invalid  label: invalid  restart: true
    commit_roadmap -> Exit
    commit_roadmap -> Exit                        when ctx.outcome = fail      label: commit_failed
